        <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="1">
            <title>Inspection and Repair Procedure</title>
            <para>We told the customer that your dealer will make this correction for you at no cost. Contact your
                dealer to make the arrangements to repair your unit. We also told the customer if you desire to make
                this inspection and/or inspection and repair yourself, you may purchase the bolts from the dealer.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent serious eye injury, always wear safe eye protection when you perform vehicle
                        maintenance or service.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Block the wheels to prevent the vehicle from moving. If a vehicle moves unexpectedly or
                        suddenly, the result could be serious personal injury or death.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>If the vehicle must be raised, do not work under a vehicle supported only by jacks. Jacks can
                        slip or fall over potentially resulting in serious personal injury or death.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <para>This repair procedure involves inspecting the bus by measuring the tightness of the subject bolts with
                a torque wrench. There are two bolts per wheel end, four-wheel ends in total. If a bolt is not properly
                torqued, it must be replaced with a new bolt.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Chock the wheels or raise onto jack stands as necessary.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a torque wrench, tighten the bolt and measure the torque.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If the torque reaches
                        <emph type="bold">110 Lbf-Ft</emph>
                        (150 Nm) without
                        <emph type="bold">any</emph>
                        movement of the bolt, then the bolt is properly torqued and no further action is required. Move
                        on to another bolt.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If the bolt moves
                        <emph type="bold">before</emph>
                        reaching the specified torque, it must be removed and replaced with a new patch bolt. See Step
                        3.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Replace the loose bolt with a new patch bolt part number 3584626C1 and torque to
                    <emph type="bold">93-107 Lbf-Ft</emph>(126-145 Nm).
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If the bolt that is located on the top portion of the caliper cannot be replaced
                        because of interference with the rear spring, both bolts must be loosened to allow the rotor to
                        move for clearance.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">In this case,
                        <emph type="bold">both bolts</emph>
                        must be replaced. See Step 4.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If both bolts had to be replaced on any wheel end, the following procedure must be
                    followed when installing the new bolts:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install new upper (top) mounting bolt FINGER tight securing the caliper to the
                        anchor plate.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Then install new lower mounting bolt FINGER tight.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">FIRST, tighten the
                        <emph type="bold">leading</emph>
                        caliper mounting bolt to
                        <emph type="bold">93-107 Lbf-Ft</emph>
                        (126-145 Nm).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">NEXT, tighten the trailing caliper mounting bolt to
                        <emph type="bold">93-107 Lbf-Ft</emph>
                        (126-145 Nm).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">See the following diagram for defining leading and trailing caliper mounting
                        bolts.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Once all of the pin bolts have been inspected and/or replaced, lower the vehicle and
                    remove the wheel chocks as necessary.
                </para>
            </step1>
